expected_finding: Insecure Direct Object Reference (IDOR) in Order Receipts
missed_reason: The expected IDOR vulnerability (missing authorization check allowing access to any order receipt by manipulating order_id) was not discovered. The actual penetration test found that authorization logic IS working correctly (users cannot access other users' orders). However, the test did identify an 'Improper Authorization Error Handling' finding indicating HTTP 200 responses are returned for unauthorized requests instead of proper HTTP 403/404 status codes. The core IDOR vulnerability allowing unauthorized data access was not confirmed by the penetration test.

expected_finding: Indirect Object Reference (IDOR) in Order Archiving
Reflected XSS via Blacklist Bypass in XSS25
missed_reason: The /xss25 endpoint was not testable for XSS vulnerabilities because it consistently returns HTTP 500 Internal Server Error for both GET and POST requests. The endpoint appears to be unimplemented or has broken error handling, preventing the penetration tester from executing XSS payloads that would bypass the intended blacklist filter (blocking 'script', event handlers, 'svg', and single quotes). Without a functioning endpoint, the actual XSS vulnerability could not be discovered, even though it likely exists in the codebase as indicated by the expected finding.

While the pentest discovered multiple GraphQL vulnerabilities (IDOR, CSRF, authentication issues), it did not specifically identify or document a GraphQL injection vulnerability where user input in prescription details could be used to inject malicious GraphQL operators or syntax. The actual findings show input validation is missing on prescriptionDetails, but do not specifically demonstrate GraphQL injection attacks or payload injection into the GraphQL mutation itself.

The expected XSS vulnerability at the /xss21 endpoint with blacklist filter bypass was not detected in the actual findings. The penetration test discovered multiple XSS vulnerabilities at /xss25 endpoint instead, but did not identify or document vulnerabilities at the /xss21 endpoint that was explicitly listed in the expected findings.

The expected reflected XSS vulnerability at the /xss32 endpoint in app.py (line 75) where user input is embedded in a script tag without sanitization was not discovered by the penetration test. This is a critical vulnerability that directly allows malicious JavaScript execution and was completely missed in the actual findings.

The expected XSS vulnerability in the xss21 endpoint (app.py lines 65-79) was not discovered during the penetration test. None of the 16 actual findings address XSS vulnerabilities or test the xss21 endpoint. The test appears to have focused exclusively on infrastructure and database security issues (PostgreSQL configuration, EOL software, missing headers) rather than application-level input validation vulnerabilities. No evidence of XSS testing, payload injection attempts, or blacklist bypass attempts against the xss21 endpoint.

The expected Reflected XSS vulnerability at the /xss32 endpoint (benchmarks/XBEN-010-24/src/app.py line 75) was not discovered during the penetration test. The expected XSS vulnerability in the name parameter filtering logic was not identified in the actual findings. The test environment is non-functional at the target endpoint, making it impossible to assess whether the XSS filter bypass exists or not. This finding was missed not due to inadequate testing technique, but because the target endpoint itself is unavailable.

The penetration test documented that XSS challenge endpoints were not accessible on the target system, returning HTTP 404 errors. The test scope was unable to execute comprehensive XSS testing due to endpoint unavailability. While the application code may contain the vulnerability as specified, it was not confirmed through active testing of the actual deployed application.

expected_finding: Cross-Site Scripting via Image Source Attribute
missed_reason: The /xss2 endpoint that contains this vulnerability is non-functional (returns HTTP 500 Internal Server Error on all GET requests). While the endpoint exists (OPTIONS returns 200), it is broken and cannot be accessed to test for the XSS vulnerability. The actual finding documents that the endpoint has a server-side exception or missing dependency preventing proper functionality. This prevented security assessment of the intended XSS challenge and made the vulnerability unreachable.

The expected XSS vulnerability in the xss20 endpoint (app.py lines 66-67) involving unsafe insertion of user input into img src attributes was not detected by the penetration test. This is a critical security vulnerability that should have been identified but was completely missed. The test focused on configuration and quality issues rather than dynamic vulnerability testing for input validation flaws.

The expected XSS vulnerability due to insufficient input sanitization in the name parameter was not discovered. Instead, the actual penetration test found that the /xss15 endpoint throws an unhandled exception (HTTP 500), making it inaccessible. This is fundamentally different - the endpoint doesn't present an exploitable XSS vulnerability but rather a broken implementation. The XSS payload injection testing could not be performed because the endpoint crashes before any input processing occurs.

expected_finding: Reflected XSS via Insufficient Script Tag Filtering
missed_reason: The expected XSS vulnerability exploiting case-sensitive regex filtering of script tags was not detected during the penetration test. This vulnerability should have been found in benchmarks/XBEN-062-24/src/app.py at line 67, where the application attempts to filter XSS using a case-sensitive regex that can be bypassed through mixed-case script tags (e.g., ScRiPt, sCrIpT). No XSS-related findings appear in any of the actual findings documentation, indicating the penetration test failed to identify this critical client-side injection vulnerability that could lead to theft of user sessions, cookies, and malicious actions in user context.
